The survey will take around 15 minutes and is voluntary. Your responses are confidential.

You will be compensated if you complete the survey and your responses pass the quality checks. These checks use statistical methods to detect incoherent and rushed responses. It is crucial for the validity of our research that you answer honestly and read the questions carefully.


For questions, contact the researcher by e-mail: Alex Gazmararian, agaz@umich.edu. 

Do you agree to participate?

column33: One issue that genuinely concerns me is how unprepared many communities are for extreme heat and bad-air-quality days that disrupt normal life. As someone who works with climate and public-opinion data, I keep seeing the same pattern: the people most affected—outdoor workers, older adults, and lower-income neighborhoods with less tree cover—often have the fewest resources to adapt. When air-quality alerts or heat spikes happen, even simple routines like walking outside or commuting feel riskier, and the unevenness of that risk becomes hard to ignore. It matters to me personally because I want resilience to be treated like basic infrastructure—shade, cooling centers that are accessible, and clear public messaging—rather than something only some people can “opt into.”
